  "prompt": "What is regression?",
  "response": "Regression is a statistical method used to understand the relationship between a dependent variable (often called the outcome or the target variable) and one or more independent variables (often called predictors or features). The goal of regression analysis is to model this relationship so that the dependent variable can be predicted based on the values of the independent variables.\n\nThere are several types of regression, including:\n\n1. **Linear Regression**: This is the simplest form of regression, where the relationship between the dependent and independent variables is modeled as a straight line. The equation typically has the form \\( y = mx + c \\), where \\( y \\) is the dependent variable, \\( x \\) is the independent variable, \\( m \\) is the slope, and \\( c \\) is the y-intercept.\n\n2. **Multiple Linear Regression**: An extension of linear regression that involves multiple independent variables. The model can be expressed as \\( y = b_0 + b_1x_1 + b_2x_2 + ... + b_nx_n \\), where \\( y \\) is the dependent variable and \\( x_1, x_2, ..., x_n \\) are independent variables.\n\n3. **Polynomial Regression**: A form of regression in which the relationship between the dependent variable and one or more independent variables is modeled as an nth-degree polynomial. This can capture more complex relationships than linear regression.\n\n4. **Logistic Regression**: Although the name suggests regression, logistic regression is used for classification problems. It predicts the probability of a binary outcome, using a logistic function (sigmoid curve).\n\n5. **Ridge and Lasso Regression**: These are types of linear regression that add regularization terms to the model to prevent overfitting. Ridge regression adds a penalty proportional to the square of the coefficients, while Lasso regression adds a penalty proportional to the absolute value of the coefficients.\n\n6. **Non-linear Regression**: Any regression model that captures a non-linear relationship between the dependent and independent variables, not fitting into specific forms like polynomial regression.\n\nRegression analysis helps to make predictions, understand causal relationships, and identify trends in data. It is widely used in fields such as finance, biology, engineering, and social sciences.",
